    <exploration>
      <p>
        Let <m>P=(x,y,z)</m> be a point in space. This point lies on a cylinder of radius <m>r</m>, where the cylinder has the <m>z</m> axis as its axis of symmetry. The height of the point is <m>z</m> units up from the <m>xy</m> plane. The point casts a shadow in the <m>xy</m> plane at <m>Q=(x,y,0)</m>. The angle between the ray <m>\vec{OQ}</m> and the <m>x</m>-axis is <m>\theta</m>. Construct a graph in 3D of this information, and use it to develop the equations for cylindrical coordinates given above.
      </p>
    </exploration>

